title: Physical Development and Health
subject: Infant and Toddler Early Learning and Development Standards (2024-)

document.title: Infant and Toddler Maine Early Learning and Development Standards (Infant Toddler MELDS)

B91673CC705E45929AD444ECED98D0B9.description:
Increased interest in helping with chores
and physical care:

991B9A3C6C994EC3BC3D6A6EBE1324F1.description:
Shows increased interest and proficiency
with toileting skills:

76DBB16D71B643759ED9E7F8F99680F2.description:
undresses self, puts on clothes (no
buttoning), shoes, jacket, hat

B181905134E94C85AA2B6A268A1403A6.description: Continues to show interest in dressing:

D6E44573A9C84866A57F20DA06CDE265.description:
sets items on table and removes after
eating

BBFF27F68F5149F68287E41C090896DE.description:
pours own water from small
container

7D0859648DEF43028E1FB5A309A40B74.description:
Progressing well with self-feeding and
self-serving:

AF05ADCA951941B2BB0CBE797DF328CF.description:
Shows interest in helping with chores,
mimics adult behavior.

760EB1DD378E43ED92837D707FF45C73.description:
Shows interest in toileting at end of this
stage:

19E2DE9F4C164285BAD4F0298BDFA62E.description:
pushes arm through sleeve, takes
clothes off, unties shoes

D24B9149C3004DCFA33A973CDAF58414.description:
Alerts caregiver in own way when
physically uncomfortable:

05CA9B050B8A4661B7CB7ABB9FB6AF66.description:
begins to hold own bottle/cup,
begins to feed self with fingers

4E7189C55637444687BAA08E43072B83.description: Can turn pages of a book.

F9B1BBF190134AEC8118BB01C57BEC11.description:
Can use paintbrush, but doesn’t control
drips.

59B6F470DF034647A70F6537DBEBB488.description: Holds spoon, fork, cup, but may still spill.

B6ED52CA5CA54D7D9BE7139180B22173.description:
brushes dolls hair, holds and winds a
music box

1AD578CBB5C847619C48614499D7107E.description:
Holds object with one hand and
manipulates it with the other:

8A2FEC5A4A0E427DAD95A6BDDCA2FD52.description: Uses a crayon to imitate marks/scribble.

92F28B513EA444D9A74FEACDB16E25F8.description: Can turn pages of a board book

30E11FC06CDA415AAA89AFE7CE200BF8.description: Begins to show preference for one hand.

C4B8BD00B22047FCA4B52A65C525416C.description: Handles a cup or spoon for self-feeding.

B6882CDF242C4D30B4335D0B82D606D9.description:
Uses thumb and forefinger to pick up
small items.

1E4A8E583171459CBBA043A9FF054F2F.description:
Brings two blocks together to make
noise.

C23DD03DAA7B4140BBF95B9258FE1190.description:
Scoops up and takes with hand to
manipulate or pick up objects, sand,
food, etc.

36214D798365489DB1624C61669A5D0F.description: Follows slow moving object with eyes.

921CD99BB129458CA0E688982BD72E20.description:
Transfers object from one hand to
another

045AC24EBA554E43804917DE39459073.description:
reaches with one arm and grasps at
will, grasps – releases – “re-grasps”
and releases again, begins to grasp
with thumb and forefinger

A1C47DC7B3884629A25801A7076F1653.description:
Reaches for objects with both arms, but
hands are fisted:

783BA6D57D7F45FB95331C56B0832157.description:
Stares at objects, especially faces;
begins to coordinate eyes.

B09ECBB86A754A5C845121CB7BFDCBEF.description:
Engages in creative movement
spontaneously and when prompted by
music or adult.

5EB01B27EEAC4EB292B944805D945865.description:
catches a ball by trapping it with
arms and hands, pounds object
with intention and precision, creates
simple block structures, pushes foot
into shoe, takes off shoes

7E4E244E9ABA4775A782DC7CC380AF63.description:
Uses arms and legs with more
purposefulness:

30B389D47B274ABE9C71B52C71001479.description:
walks fast, walks on tiptoes, walks
backwards, walks upstairs holding
a railing (or hand), runs with control,
climbs well, throws a ball with aim,
may jump in place, may balance
briefly on 1 foot, rides tricycle

653F085F864443428F0954F2867F2DB6.description:
Exhibits more control and coordination of
large muscle and body movement:

F5829D8BDBB64C9B82F0E47A8CB04D0D.description:
throws, carries, pushes, pulls, dumps
objects, scoots on or rides wheel toys
without pedals

54A843D257424521888327D98D694D0C.description:
Uses arms and legs with increasing
purposefulness:

B45A357F9D134A7292C05EAE5B03965B.description:
sits up, crawls or creeps, pulls to
stand, cruises while holding on to
furniture, stands alone, climbs out
of crib, walks alone, runs with a wide
stance, walks upstairs holding a hand,
stops and walks backwards a few
steps, climbs simple structures

6749D8C05C5F4195A38AEAEBD7112B7B.description:
Exhibits increasing control of large
muscles and body movement:

A99C61DAEDAB45EEAB31CF425A565D13.description:
claps hands, pounds on things, kicks
at objects, holds arms out for jacket
or so shirt can be taken off

FAD16E00539C478789E06BD3CC924102.description:
Begins to use arms and legs
purposefully:

99CB13E77248480294FB1D7924FF548A.description:
turns from back to stomach and
stomach to back, moves by rolling,
inches forward on stomach or back,
sits unsupported, begins bouncing
when held

A802F188A76549ACA02CBB8A7E4AB170.description:
head control, lifts chin, lifts head, lifts
both head and shoulders, supports
self on flexed elbows

DA2D09BF8FF24D6AAF90460165F7EA19.description:
Exhibits beginning stages of large
muscle control:

AB0A5C4A64BA4414929487F74E0B87C7.description:
ability to isolate familiar sounds in
tandem with cognitive development
(i.e. hears siren outside, points and
says, “Fire truck!”)

5C88F5AEAAA44AF0A9F0BF07C63F71CB.description:
ability to discriminate finer detail in
tandem with cognitive development
(i.e. may notice caregiver’s earring)

DB1AE2A22C844EB0B0AF0FD226547EA4.description:
increased cognitive and motor skills
allows increased ability to explore
and form meaning from sensory
information

64F630569F2D42C39F0EF82776806AB7.description:
continues to show increased ability
to concentrate with multiple sensory
stimulation present

76DF5D53746A4B2F8EB5692DFD36397C.description:
Sensory thresholds do not interfere with
desire to explore surroundings:

2662495A6A8E40CB856386C452A949DF.description:
Hearing information more refined: ability
to discriminate sounds in a noisy setting.

6E41BE70728147B78E90872D229CEC8C.description:
depth perception established; seeks
and responds to increased visual
stimulation

C08D8AB589124DA388825763D466F11A.description:
shows increased enjoyment of
varieties of sensory information

34C0BCAC0ED64938B91561CCE4845502.description:
oral exploration of objects decreases
with age

28D17BC9A4D0473EB9738034B749074F.description:
shows increased desire to explore
sensory information

99DBC33A73D344F7B5D4403EDC5B9690.description:
shows increased ability to
concentrate and begin to show
sustained interest in people, objects
and activities

B839E2E8BB394E8299CF4D032327CE23.description:
Continue to integrate information
gathered from the senses:

57B261F0906B400AB3246CF24883211F.description:
Respond to what they see (i.e. move
toward desired person or object, look for
source of noise).

8479A1418ED5407AABEDF34B07276CB5.description:
Can distinguish smell of mother from
others.

B464BC3750A6423AB3584971D76C952D.description:
Shows enjoyment of motion such as
rocking, jiggling, bouncing, or being
carried around.

5BF9D106F79648EDA84474319E0C0B4E.description:
Can distinguish parents’ voice from that
of a stranger.

10838B228F9640CCA4101E88663DA490.description:
Preference for slower, high pitched
sounds.

33E449A6F82C4E77A7B001E3E1E1B53D.description:
Increased ability to detect detail and
coordinate visual information from each
eye.

A36B36E9029B45ADA8CD0D8904CC8346.description:
Initially visual system immature (attentive
to objects of contrasting colors).

F963BBA69E824438BFEFC389A5FF4E36.description:
Reflexes that develop after birth: bicycle
kicking, body follows turn of head, and
protects self when falling.

07390F9FB3014C9AB66C93CBF063F0C5.description:
Reflexes at birth: stepping, palmar grasp,
startle reflex, rooting and sucking, handto-mouth, and moves arms in swimming
motion.
